Pour the @water{300%milliliter}(for the rice) into a #medium saucepan{} with a
tight-fitting #lid{}.

Stir in the @Basmati Rice{150%grams} and @salt{1/4%tsp} and bring to the boil.
Once boiling, turn the heat down to medium and cover with the lid.

Leave to cook for ~{10%minutes}, then remove the pan from the heat (still
covered) and leave to the side for another ~{10%minutes} or until ready to
serve (the rice will continue to cook in its own steam).

Meanwhile, peel and grate the @garlic clove{2} (or use a #garlic press{}).

Drain the @firm tofu{250%grams} and thoroughly pat dry with #kitchen paper{}.
Tear into 3cm chunks and pop into a #medium bowl{}.

Sprinkle over the @plain flour{1%tbsp} and @salt{1/4%tsp} for the tofu. Toss
together so the tofu is nicely coated.

Heat a drizzle of @oil{drizzle} in a #large frying pan{} on high heat.

Once hot, fry the tofu until slightly crispy, ~{8-10%minutes}. Turn frequently
to ensure it doesn't burn.

Meanwhile, clean out the tofu bowl. Once the tofu is crispy, transfer it to the
(now clean) bowl and set aside for later.

Wipe out the (now empty) pan and pop back onto medium heat with a drizzle of
@oil{drizzle}.

Add the garlic, @korma curry paste{50%grams} and @curry powder mix{1%sachet}.
Fry for ~{30%seconds}.

Next, stir in the @vegetable stock paste{10%grams}, @mango chutney{40%grams}
and @water{150%milliliter}(for the sauce). Bring to the boil, then lower the
heat.

Add the tofu back into the pan and simmer until the liquid has reduced slightly,
~{2-3%minutes}.

Stir in the @creme fraiche{75%grams} and @butter{20%grams}.

Add the @baby spinach{40%grams} to the pan a handful at a time until wilted
and piping hot, ~{1-2%minutes}. Season with @salt{} and @pepper{} and remove
from the heat.

Add a splash more @water{} if you feel it needs it.

Share the rice out between your #serving bowls{}.

Spoon over the curry. Sprinkle on the @crispy onions{1%sachet} to finish.

Enjoy!

> 'Palak' is Hindi for spinach, the iron-rich leafy green in this mildly spiced,
> creamy curry - not to be confused with 'saag', which means any kind of leafy
> greens! Firm tofu, made from compressed soybeans, is the perfect vehicle for
> soaking up the delicious flavours.